sketch:
The post-theorem introduction does not give a step-by-step proof sketch for the main theorem, but it outlines the proof structure of the paper: next the authors “set up the regularity structure framework” and “divide the strategy into a deterministic and probabilistic statement,” then prove the former. We first prove the following lemma. \begin{lemma}\label{lem:equivalence}
Under Assumptions \ref{asn:data} and \ref{asn:area-model}, if $U\in\cD_{\sol}(\Gamma)$ is a solution to \eqref{eq:abstract-gPAM-old}
with respect to the model $(\Pi,\Gamma)$ defined in \eqref{eq:area-model},
then $V=\iota U$ belongs to $\cD_{\sol}'(\Gamma')$ and is a solution to
\begin{equ}\label{eq:abstract-gPAM-new}
V=\mathcal{P}\Big(\widehat{gg'}(V)\,\<AEta>\Big)
\end{equ}
with respect to the model $(\Pi',\Gamma')$.
\end{lemma}
They then formulate precisely the latter. We first prove the following theorem. \begin{theorem}\label{thm:convergence}
Let $\kappa\in(0,1/100)$ and let $c_\rho>0$ be the constant defined in \eqref{eq:c-whitenoise}. Let $\<Eta>$ be $c_\rho$ times a $2$-dimensional spatial white noise and let $\<EtaIEta>$ be the Wick product of $\<Eta>$ and $\<IEta>$. Then they almost surely satisfy Assumption \ref{asn:area-model} and $(\hat \Pi^\eps,\hat \Gamma^\eps)\to(\Pi,\Gamma)$ in law in $\cM_\kappa$, where $(\Pi, \Gamma)$ is as in \eqref{eq:area-model}.
\end{theorem}
Finally they “give the proof of the main result modulo these two statements.” Next they “prove the theorem above, a statement on the convergence of a sequence of BPHZ models,” noting that “the limit is \emph{not} a BPHZ model.”

